 egin{def}
Let $M \subset \mathbb{R}^N$ be an $n$-dimensional affine set with $0 < n < N$, and set $m := N - n$. A \emph{Tucker representation} of $M$ is a representation obtained after a permutation of coordinates, in which every vector $x = (\xi_1, \dots, \xi_N) \in \mathbb{R}^N$ belongs to $M$ if and only if its coordinates satisfy a system of affine equations of the form

\[ \xi_{n+i} = \alpha_{i1} \xi_1 + \cdots + \alpha_{in} \xi_n + \alpha_i, \qquad i = 1, \dots, m. \]

Equivalently, a Tucker representation expresses $M$ as the graph of an affine transformation from $\mathbb{R}^n$ to $\mathbb{R}^m$. In the special case where $M$ is a linear subspace, the constants $\alpha_i$ vanish and the representation is homogeneous. 
\end{def}
